channel.title: NASA Image of the Day
channel.description: The latest NASA "Image of the Day" image.

item.title: The Barchan Dunes of Brazil
item.description: Former NASA astronaut Jack Fischer captured this photograph of Lagoa dos Barros and crescent-shaped barchan dunes on the Atlantic coastline of southern Brazil on July 9, 2017, while aboard the International Space Station.

item.title: Webb’s First Deep Field
item.description: President Joe Biden unveiled this image of the galaxy cluster SMACS 0723 during a White House event on July 11, 2022.

item.title: Wildlife at Armstrong Flight Research Center
item.description: A bobcat surveys the landscape at NASA’s Armstrong Flight Research Center in Edwards, California in this March 11, 2021, image.

item.title: New Horizons’ Infrared View
item.description: NASA's New Horizons spacecraft captured this high-resolution enhanced color view of Charon, Pluto's largest moon, just before closest approach on July 14, 2015.

item.title: Prelaunch Processing for Psyche
item.description: NASA's Psyche spacecraft is nearly complete as it rests in a clean room on June 26, 2023, at Astrotech Space Operations Facility near the agency’s Kennedy Space Center in Florida.

item.title: The Last Rays of an Orbital Sunset
item.description: The last rays of an orbital sunset begin fading in Earth's atmosphere silhouetting the cloud tops.

item.title: NASA’s X-59 Makes a Critical Move
item.description: NASA’s X-59 research aircraft moves from its construction site to the flight line – or the space between the hangar and the runway – at Lockheed Martin Skunk Works in Palmdale, California, on June 16, 2023.

item.title: A Full Moon Illuminates Artemis I
item.description: A full moon was visible behind the Artemis I SLS (Space Launch System) rocket and Orion spacecraft at Launch Complex 39B at NASA's Kennedy Space Center in Florida on June 14, 2022. The first in an increasingly complex series of missions, Artemis I tested SLS and Orion as an integrated system prior to crewed flights to the Moon.

item.title: Hubble Checks in on a Galactic Neighbor
item.description: The highly irregular galaxy ESO 174-1, which resembles a lonely, hazy cloud against a backdrop of bright stars, dominates this image from the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope.

item.title: Artemis II Heat Shield Installed
item.description: Teams install the heat shield on the Artemis II Orion spacecraft at NASA’s Kennedy Space Center in Florida on June 22, 2023.

item.title: Rising to the Challenge: NASA TechRise Student Teams Take Flight
item.description: Students from 20 middle and high schools watched as their experiments launched aboard a high-altitude balloon on June 14 as part of NASA’s TechRise Student Challenge.

item.title: Exploring Climate Data in a New Way
item.description: Local students take in the sights—and data—at an Earth Information Center student engagement event, Friday, June 23, 2023, at NASA Headquarters in Washington.

item.title: Hubble Glimpses a Glistening Cluster
item.description: The teeming stars of the globular cluster NGC 6544 glisten in this image from the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope.

item.title: One Last Look from Skylab 2
item.description: During the Skylab 2 crew's final fly-around inspection on June 22, 1973, they saw this overhead view of the Skylab Space Station.

item.title: The Glowing North Sea
item.description: As sunlight and warmth increase in the spring and summer, the North Sea starts to gain swirls and tendrils of color.

item.title: It's Rock Science
item.description: Astronauts Reid Wiseman of NASA (left), Jeremy Hansen of the Canadian Space Agency (middle), and Victor Glover of NASA (right) pay close attention to Moon samples as they receive a lesson in the Apollo Lunar Lab at NASA's Johnson Space Center in Houston on May 9, 2023.

item.title: A View of Galveston, the Birthplace of Juneteenth
item.description: This image of Galveston was taken by the Expedition 67 crew aboard the International Space Station on June 20, 2022, as it orbited 224 miles above.

item.title: Artemis II Module Makes a Move
item.description: The European Service Module for the Artemis II Orion spacecraft moves into the Final Assembly and System Testing Cell at NASA's Kennedy Space Center in this image from May 22, 2023.

item.title: A Dragon Beams Up
item.description: In this long exposure photo from June 5, 2023, a SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket creates a beam of light as it launches from Kennedy Space Center in Florida.

item.title: Spacewalker Woody Hoburg Rides the Canadarm2 Robotic Arm
item.description: Spacewalker Woody Hoburg rides the Canadarm2 robotic arm while maneuvering a roll-out solar array toward the International Space Station's truss structure.

item.title: Systems Engineering Supervisor Amy Lendian
item.description: "So here I am, a transgender woman, an engineer, working at Kennedy Space Center, and I get to work around these really smart, wonderful people, supporting the Artemis mission, sitting in the control room during the launch." — Amy Lendian, Systems Engineering Supervisor, Amentum Spaceport, NASA's Kennedy Space Center

item.title: Hubble Observes a Cosmic Sea Creature
item.description: The jellyfish galaxy JO206 trails across this image from the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope.

item.title: A Cloudy Approach
item.description: The last rays of an orbital sunset illuminate the cloud tops above the Pacific Ocean off the coast of Japan, providing a dramatic background for the SpaceX CRS-28 Dragon cargo craft as it approached the International Space Station for docking on June 6, 2023.

item.title: Crew-5 Visits NASA Headquarters
item.description: On June 5, 2023, Crew-5 astronauts Josh Cassada (left) and Nicole A. Mann (second from left) of NASA, and Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency (JAXA) astronaut Koichi Wakata (right) visited NASA Associate Administrator Bob Cabana (second from right) at NASA Headquarters in Washington.

item.title: A Bloom in Space
item.description: This colorful zinnia, shown in an image from Jan. 22, 2016, grew aboard the International Space Station as part of the VEG-01 experiment.

item.title: U.S. Poet Laureate Ada Limón Unveils Poem for Europa Clipper
item.description: U.S. Poet Laureate Ada Limón reads her poem for the Europa Clipper mission during an event with NASA, Thursday, June 1, 2023, at the Library of Congress in Washington.

item.title: NASA TV Executive Producer Rebecca Sirmons
item.description: "'NASA for all.' That's something that I think is really important because we are the universe, right? We are made of star stuff, and I think now more than ever, we all need to remember that we're part of a greater purpose." – Rebecca Sirmons, NASA TV Executive Producer, NASA Headquarters

item.title: Computer Programmer and Mathematician Josephine Jue
item.description: Hired by NASA’s Johnson Space Center in Houston in 1963, Josephine Jue was a Chinese-American computer programmer and mathematician who worked for the agency for more than 30 years.

item.title: VIPER Team Mimics Moon's Surface
item.description: By recreating realistic Moon-like environments, we can get a much better idea of how VIPER will perform on the surface.

item.title: TROPICS Prepped to Track Storms
item.description: A Rocket Lab Electron rocket stands on Pad B, Launch Complex 1, in Māhia, New Zealand, just ahead of a successful launch on Friday, May 26, with NASA’s Time-Resolved Observations of Precipitation structure and storm Intensity with a Constellation of Smallsats (TROPICS) CubeSats payload.

item.title: Hubble Captures a Drifting Galaxy
item.description: The jellyfish galaxy JW39 hangs serenely in this image from the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope.

item.title: Strategic Partnerships Manager Anita Dey
item.description: "If I can advocate for all the groups that need equity, I'm glad to do it." – Anita Dey, Strategic Partnerships Manager, Outreach and Engagement, NASA Headquarters

item.title: Whistling Through the Wildflowers
item.description: Two black-bellied whistling ducks walk through a field of wildflowers at Kennedy Space Center in Florida on May 19, 2023.

item.title: SpaceX Dragon Crew Ship Approaches the International Space Station
item.description: The SpaceX Dragon crew spacecraft, named Freedom, is seen as it approaches the International Space Station with four Axiom Mission 2 private astronauts aboard on Monday, May 22, 2023.

item.title: Baby Stars in the Orion Constellation
item.description: Scores of baby stars shrouded by dust are revealed in this infrared image of the star-forming region NGC 2174.

item.title: Hubble Peers into a Glistening Star Cluster
item.description: The densely packed globular cluster NGC 6325 glistens in this image from the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope.

item.title: U.S. Senate Members Meet the Crew of Artemis II
item.description: The four astronauts who will fly around the Moon on NASA’s Artemis II visited Washington on Wednesday, May 17, to discuss their upcoming mission with members of Congress and others.

item.title: Laguna San Rafael National Park Viewed from the Space Station
item.description: Laguna San Rafael National Park, photographed on May 9, 2023 as the space station orbited 268 miles above Chile.

item.title: Moon Over the Southern Atlantic
item.description: The waxing gibbous Moon stands out against the stark darkness of space on May 3, 2023.

item.title: Hearing and Seeing the Music of the Spheres
item.description: Maestro Piotr Gajewski conducts the National Philharmonic in the world premiere performance of Henry Dehlinger’s “Cosmic Cycles,” in this photo from Thursday, May 11, 2023, as an enhanced color image of Jupiter is displayed above.

item.title: 50th Anniversary of the Skylab 1 Launch
item.description: Clouds of smoke billow out over the surrounding area as the uncrewed Skylab 1/Saturn V space vehicle launches from NASA’s Kennedy Space Center on May 14, 1973.

item.title: Stabilizing Shorelines with Mangroves
item.description: A team member from the Environmental Management Branch at NASA’s Kennedy Space Center works to remove a mangrove seedling deposited by tropical winds on the shoreline of KARS Park at Kennedy in this image from April 12, 2023.

item.title: Vance Oyama, Searching for Life in Our Solar System
item.description: Vance I. Oyama holds a readout from the gas chromatograph in the life detection laboratory at NASA’s Ames Research Center in this picture from April 22, 1965.

item.title: Spacewalkers Stephen Bowen and Sultan Alneyadi Exit the Quest Airlock
item.description: Spacewalkers Stephen Bowen and Sultan Alneyadi are pictured in their Extravehicular Mobility Units, or spacesuits, exiting the International Space Station's Quest airlock and beginning a spacewalk.

item.title: Plumes from Popocatépetl Volcano
item.description: Popocatépetl, one of Mexico’s most active volcanoes, has been erupting since 2005.

item.title: Eyes on Ice
item.description: Curtis Flack (left) and Paul von Hardenberg inspect the ice formation on the spinner of an Advanced Air Mobility proprotor model tested in the Icing Research Tunnel at NASA’s Glenn Research Center in Cleveland.

item.title: Exploring the Cosmos Together
item.description: Miloslav Stašek, Ambassador of the Czech Republic to the United States (left), Foreign Affairs Minister for the Czech Republic, Jan Lipavský (second from left), NASA Administrator Bill Nelson (second from right), and Acting Assistant Secretary of State for Oceans and International Environmental and Scientific Affairs Jennifer R. Littlejohn (right),

item.title: Hubble Captures Extraordinarily Bright Interacting Galaxies
item.description: This new image from NASA’s Hubble Space Telescope shows interacting galaxies known as AM 1214-255.

item.title: Neutron Stars Collide
item.description: Two neutron stars begin to merge in this illustration, blasting a jet of high-speed particles and producing a cloud of debris.

item.title: Astronaut Kjell Lindgren
item.description: "I think that getting to be a crewmember on the International Space Station, and getting to serve there over the course of two long-duration stays, we really feel like we are bridge-builders." — Kjell Lindgren, Astronaut, NASA's Johnson Space Center

item.title: Hubble Captures an Elusive Galaxy Cluster
item.description: A menagerie of interesting astronomical finds are visible in this image from the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope.

item.title: The Cygnus space freighter is released from the Canadarm2 robotic arm
item.description: The Cygnus space freighter is pictured moments after its release from the Canadarm2 robotic arm.

item.title: Celebrating Earth Day
item.description: Former NASA Administrator Charlie Bolden speaks with local students during an Earth Day event, Thursday, April 20, 2023, at Union Station in Washington.

item.title: SuperBIT Sees Colliding Antennae Galaxies
item.description: This view of the Antennae Galaxies, two large galaxies colliding 60 million light-years away, is one of the first research images from the Super Pressure Balloon Imaging Telescope (SuperBIT) that launched on a scientific super pressure balloon April 16, 2023 (local time New Zealand).

item.title: NASA's New 3D-Printed Superalloy Can Take the Heat
item.description: NASA has demonstrated a breakthrough in 3D printable high-temperature materials that could lead to stronger, more durable parts for airplanes and spacecraft.

item.title: Martian Milestone for Ingenuity
item.description: This April 16, 2023, enhanced color image of NASA's Ingenuity Mars Helicopter is the clearest view of the rotorcraft since its first flight.

item.title: Katmai National Park
item.description: The Valley of Ten Thousand Smokes, located in Katmai National Park, forms a unique and ashen landscape. Encircled by volcanoes – both active and inactive – it has served as a perfect collection area for huge amounts of volcanic ash.

item.title: Astronaut Jessica Watkins
item.description: "Operating the International Space Station requires an entire team of people all coming together with one goal in pursuit of that one mission." — Jessica Watkins, Astronaut, NASA's Johnson Space Center

item.title: The Himalayas and Mount Everest in Nepal
item.description: Clouds gather over Nepal near Mount Everest (center) in this April 13, 2023, photograph from the International Space Station.

item.title: Bald Eagle Lands at Kennedy Space Center
item.description: An American bald eagle swoops down to land on a pole at NASA’s Kennedy Space Center on April 10, 2023.
